Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:06 AM Defendant Hans P Rohne in court.  Attorney Priya Barnes in court for Hans P Rohne.  Prosecuting attorney Andrew Nesheim in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Case called for review of competency report filed 8/23/22.
Attorney Barnes is not challenging the doctor's report.  Defendant does not wish to challenge the report.
State is not challenging the doctor's report.
The Court finds the defendant is not competent to proceed at this time, but if provided with appropriate medication and treatment, is likely to attain competency within statutory time limits.  
The Court, upon making the finding, suspends the criminal proceedings.
Review hearing scheduled for December 5, 2022 at 09:00 am.
Review hearing on December 5, 2022 at 09:00 am.
Review hearing on August 24, 2022 at 10:00 am.

If DNA sample has not been taken from the defendant, the Court orders sample to be taken;  and it may be expunged under 165.77(4) Wis. Statutes. Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing.  Defendant to have no contact with victim A/witnesses A & B (EXCEPTION: 3rd party contact for the sole purpose of an insurance claim) listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.  Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle/motorcycle unless properly licensed.  Comply with all licensing restrictions.

Repayment at the rate of $50.00 per month commencing August 15, 2022. (BC)

LF 7/25--sent to BC; mailed copy of signed Order and payment letter to defendant.
